	(text "1. LoRa Transceiver Recommendation\n\nIt would be better to replace the bare LoRa \ntransceiver IC with a pre-certified LoRa module. \nOtherwise, the RF front-end, including the impedance \nmatching network, antenna matching, and PCB RF \nlayout, would need to be designed and validated \nin-house, which is a complex process. Since the \nreference RF design is not fully public, achieving \nhigh RF performance is challenging. With the current \nbare-chip implementation, the expected communication \nrange is unlikely to exceed 1.2 km in Line-of-Sight\n(LOS) conditions, assuming approximately 12 dBm \ntransmit power, while Non-Line-of-Sight (NLOS) \nperformance may drop below 180 m depending on \nthe environment. Therefore, I strongly recommend \nreplacing the bare LoRa IC with a LoRa module.\n\n2. Module Selection and PCB Changes\n\nIf we switch to a LoRa module, a new PCB footprint \nwill need to be created to accommodate it. \nAdditionally, low-cost modules should be avoided, \nas they generally provide lower RF performance. Instead, \nit is recommended to use a high-quality module, such \nas those offered by Seeed Studio, which can provide \nup to +22 dBm transmit power along with an optimized \nRF design. Such modules can achieve communication \ndistances of approximately 22 km in LOS conditions \nand around 600 m or more in challenging NLOS \nenvironments, depending on antenna selection, terrain, \ninterference, and regulatory transmit power limits.\n\n3. FootPrint Missing\nThe Coaxial Cable connector is still in development "
		(exclude_from_sim no)
		(at 157.48 194.056 0)
		(effects
			(font
				(size 1.778 1.778)
			)
			(justify left)
		)
		(uuid "80936b45-eae7-49a7-960f-a67cce120c66")
	)
